{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17489700","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17489700"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T04:26:46+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T04:26:46+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"721"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"721","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/721"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.13,0.1,0.66,0.03,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"721"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"90689"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"721","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/721"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"721"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74857"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"518"},{"type":"tags","id":"1139"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1292"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31110"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"90689","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/90689"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 72-year-old woman presents to her General Practice clinic with a three-month history of increasing tiredness and breathlessness. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. She is a non-smoker and drinks one glass of wine a day.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears pale. Her pulse rate is 100/min, blood pressure 130/95mmHg, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. The cardiorespiratory and abdominal examinations are normal, apart from some fullness in the right iliac fossa. Her haemoglobin is 75 g/L (125/160). A CT scan is performed and a representative image shown (Image). Apart from what this scan shows, the investigation does not find any other abnormalities.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Apart from correction of her anaemia, which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["CT-guided biopsy","Laparoscopy","Colonoscopy","MRI scan","PET scan"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe scan shows a solid mass in the caecum, occupying some 50% of the lumen. This is almost certainly a carcinoma of the caecum. The next step will be to confirm the diagnosis with a \u003Cstrong\u003Ecolonoscopy\u003C/strong\u003E. Whilst for many intra-abdominal masses the approach might be \u003Cstrong\u003ECT-guided biopsy\u003C/strong\u003E or \u003Cstrong\u003Elaparoscopic biopsy\u003C/strong\u003E, such techniques would be inappropriate for suspected colonic neoplasms, particularly where the tumour appears to be confined to the bowel. Tissue samples can be obtained colonoscopically. At the same time the tumour mass can be identified visually and synchronous disease be excluded from other sites in the colon.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMRI scans\u003C/strong\u003E are useful in the assessment of primary rectal neoplasms and the assessment of liver lesions, but would not be the next investigation in this instance. Likewise, \u003Cstrong\u003EPET scan imaging\u003C/strong\u003E does not have a clear role.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["A tissue biopsy is always important when making the diagnosis of a gastrointestinal tract malignancy."],"references":["Dekker E, Tanis PJ, Vleugels JLA, Kasi PM, Wallace MB. Colorectal cancer. Lancet. 2019;394(10207):1467-1480. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/31631858/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74857"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"721"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"15006"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"15006","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/15006"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/8df32d8b-ffcc-4e12-a0ff-926a72c7d240.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/8df32d8b-ffcc-4e12-a0ff-926a72c7d240.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":587,"height":422}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74857","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/74857"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-14T14:46:25+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-14T14:46:25+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"721"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"90689"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/65"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Investigations","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"